  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There are several important legal precedents related to money laundering cases. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United States v. Sanchez (1991)\n- Established criteria for proving intent in money laundering\n- Emphasized prosecution must demonstrate willful concealment of funds\n\n2. Bank of Credit and Commerce International (BCCI) case (1991)\n- Significant international money laundering investigation\n- Highlighted cross-border financial crime complexities\n\n3. Proceeds of Crime Act (UK, 2002)\n- Expanded legal definitions of money laundering\n- Enhanced investigative and prosecution powers\n\n4. United States v. Rapp (2003)\n- Clarified standards for proving money laundering conspiracy\n- Established guidelines for tracing illicit financial transactions\n\n5. United States v. Santos (2008)\n- Supreme Court decision interpreting money laundering statute\n- Refined understanding of \"specified unlawful activity\"\n\nThese precedents have helped shape legal frameworks and investigative approaches to money laundering. However, I recommend consulting legal professionals for comprehensive, current analysis.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific cases or provide additional context?",
